RAMP

RAMP = Robust analytics for malaria policy

A-U-R-O-G

  • Analytics - decision support that is based on a systematic analysis of the evidence

  • Uncertainty - the analysis should characterize, quantify, and propagate uncertainty

  • Robust - the advice would not change if the analysis had been done in a slightly different, but reasonable way

  • Options - the endpoint is to recommend a specific course of action, but to discuss other policies that were nearly as good

  • Gaps - what new information could resolve the uncertainty

Aurog, the destroyer?

The Challenge

Complexity

Malaria is a locally peculiar, exogenously-forced, managed, complex adaptive system

malaria is so moulded and altered by local conditions that it becomes a thousand different diseases and epidemiological puzzles. Like chess, it is played with a few pieces, but is capable of an infinite variety of situations. Hackett, 1937

  • Multiple, Interacting Agents - mosquitoes, humans, parasites, and managers

  • Non-linear Dynamics - Malaria infection dynamics and immunity, blood feeding, human behaviors, and mosquito population regulation introduce strongly non-linear relationships among the variables

  • Local Peculiarity - Differences in the behavior & ecology of humans and vectors including differences in the composition of vector populations and some local differences can be the cause of enormous variance in the outcomes of malaria control

  • Exogenously forced - Mosquito populations and parasite development area are affected by temperature, rainfall, hydrology, land use changes, and other factors. Changes in transmission caused by weather can mask successes or failures of malaria control

  • Malaria Control - There are many interventions against malaria that are partially effective, depending on the local context. How should interventions be combined to best effect?

  • Spatial Dynamics - Important concepts, such as intervention coverage and effect sizes have a spatial dimension that has been poorly studied.

  • Malaria Epidemiology - Because of the complexity of malaria, there is uncertainty about some of the most important questions, such as the relationship between exposure, infection, disease, and the malaria burden in populations and for individuals over their lifetime; the indirect effects of malaria; the role of anemia; the long-term benefits of vaccines, and etc.

  • Heterogeneity - Malaria exposure risk and transmission is highly heterogeneous over space and time, which affect the expected outcomes of malaria control.

    • Macro-scale - The average intensity of malaria transmission and its seasonal pattern varies enormously over its geographical range

    • Micro-scale - The risk of malaria exposure varies at a very fine spatial grain.

    • Seasonality - The risk of malaria exposure varies over the course of a year

    • Trends - Malaria can go up or down over sustained periods of time.

    • Outbreaks - Malaria outbreaks can occur in response to

  • Evolution - The systems are constantly changing

    • Parasites evolve resistance to anti-malarial drugs, diagnostics

    • Vectors evolve resistance to insecticides

    • Donors evolve resistance to pleas for help

  • Development - The world is getting wealthier, and wealthy people can take charge of their own health

  • Uncertainty - The interactions among all these factors are a source of uncertainty about malaria

Why Model Malaria?

Why model malaria?

  • The complexity of malaria exceeds our innate mental capabilities. We can extend these capabilities by building and analyzing mathematical models.

  • Models can play a role in synthesizing information about:

    • mosquito ecology & behavior

    • human demography & behavior

    • health systems

    • vector control

    • weather

    • the evolution of resistance

Pipelines

Managing malaria involves working across three epochs of time

Stable software ecosystems facilitate development of procedures and protocols to understand our current situation, and that rigorously and routinely translate evidence from the past into advice about the future.

  • Past - all of the data we have comes from the past

  • Present - with well-developed data systems to keep us updated on the current state of the system in stable formats

  • Future - all of our decisions affect the future

Collaboration

To manage complex systems, experts must collaborate in a multi-disciplinary setting.

  • Using existing systems, it is difficult to build models that were complex in more than one way. It is difficult to build model ensembles.

  • Individual-based models are an exception to this rule, but the output of IBMs is itself highly complex. To run and analyze IBMs requires an additional, specialized set of skills.

  • In a collaborative setting it should be possible to combine and reuse models that have already been developed

  • To manage malaria, there should be an interface with algorithms that fit models to malaria data

  • The analysis should serve the needs of malaria programs (i.e. rather than to publish papers)

Why Software?

  • Replicability - To make our analysis easy for others to replicate

  • Scalable Complexity - To build model ensembles at any level of abstraction or realism that could fully propagate uncertainty

  • Transparency - To make our analysis easy to understand and critique

  • Innovation - To identify and fill gaps

Missing Skills

Existing models may not be up to the tasks we ask of them

Malaria Epidemiology

Malaria epidemiology, defined narrowly, is complex enough to strangle a goat

  • Exposure

  • Infection and super-infection

  • Complex time-course of infection with fluctuating parasite densities

  • Diagnostics and parasite detection

  • Immunity

  • Infectiousness

  • Treatment & Chemoprotection

  • Disease

    • including mild, moderate, and severe disease

    • cerebral malaria

    • malaria anemia

    • malaria in pregnancy

    • low birth weights

The packages

\(\oplus\)

Five software packages have been developed to support RAMP:

  • exDE is a set of algorithms to build and solve systems of differential equations describing the epidemiology, transmission dynamics, and control of malaria and other mosquito-transmitted pathogens. It is an open-access R package on github, including documentation and vignettes.

  • MicroMoB is a set of algorithms to build and solve discrete time systems describing the epidemiology, transmission dynamics, and control of malaria and other mosquito-transmitted pathogens. It is an open-access R package on github, including documentation and vignettes.

  • mobwork is a set of algorithms to build an analytics pipeline using exDE and MicroMoB. It is an open-access R package on github, including documentation and vignettes.

  • pf.memory is a set of algorithms that implement a probabilistic approach to malaria epidemiology, defined in the narrow sense to include exposure, infection, disease, immunity, treatment and chemoprotection, and detection. It is an open-access R package on github, including documentation and vignettes.

  • motrap.micro is a set of algorithms that implement a probabilistic approach to malaria epidemiology, defined in the narrow sense to include exposure, infection, disease, immunity, treatment and chemoprotection, and detection. It is an open-access R package on github, including documentation and vignettes.

Design Principles

RAMP software is designed for nimble model building, to build and analyze model ensembles, and to scale complexity from simple & abstract, up to highly realistic.

  • Modularity

  • Flexibility

  • Extensibility
